727757f-c.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 62nd Avenue
727757f-c.text:
Queens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 62nd Avenue, showing
the Mrs. Howard House, a pre-Revolutionary farmhouse. It was at
one time a parsonage and was also known as the Robert Odekirk farm-
house. The R. and J. Thompsons were the owners from 1852 to 1896.
The Rego Park Construction Company later established its real estate
office here.
View 2 shows the rear of the house, seen from 57th Avenue.
In 1936 the house was occupied by the Tomahawk Regular Democratic
Club.
View 1: P. L. Sperr  June 8, 1927
NO REPRODUCTIONS
View 2: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection May, 1900
MAY BE REPRODUCED
View 3: P. L. Sperr  June 29, 1936
NO REPRODUTIONS

727755f-d.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 62nd Avenue
727755f-d.text:
Cueens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 62nd Avenue, showiigg
the Mrs. Howard House, also known as the Robert Odekirk farmhouse
and was at one time used as a parsonage by ministers of the Firat
Presbyterian Church of Newtown. The house was owned by the R. and
J. Thompsons from 1852 to 1896. Later it was purchased by the Rego
Park Construction Company and used as a real estste office. The
home dates back to pre-Revolutionary days. Eugene L. Armbruster
is authority for the above data. View 4 shows the rear of the house.
W a  View 1: 1922
Views 2,3: April 1923
Viow 4: Fehruary 1924
